scenarioDescription:
The HD 219134 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 219134 is a star with 0.81 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.78 times its radius. It is located 21.2979868 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 11 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 219134 is known to have 6 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 219134 system

HD 219134 f

HD 219134 f was discovered by the Multiple Observatories observatory using the Radial Velocity method. The mass of HD 219134 f is 7.3 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 219134 f is 1.31 that of Earth. At 7.3 Earth masses, HD 219134 f is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.

At more than 10 Earth masses, HD 219134 d is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system.
